{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Saving and reading fields\n",
    "\n",
    "There are three main file formats to which a `discretisedfield.Field` object can be saved:\n",
    "\n",
    "- [VTK](https://vtk.org/) for visualisation using e.g., [ParaView](https://www.paraview.org/) or [Mayavi](https://docs.enthought.com/mayavi/mayavi/)\n",
    "- OOMMF [Vector Field File Format (OVF)](https://math.nist.gov/oommf/doc/userguide12a5/userguide/Vector_Field_File_Format_OV.html) for exchanging fields with micromagnetic simulators.\n",
    "- HDF5\n",
    "\n",
    "Let us say we have a nanosphere sample:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$x^2 + y^2 + z^2 <= r^2$$\n",
    "\n",
    "with $r=5\\,\\text{nm}$. The space is discretised into cells with dimensions $(0.5\\,\\text{nm}, 0.5\\,\\text{nm}, 0.5\\,\\text{nm})$. The value of the field at $(x, y, z)$ point is $(-cy, cx, cz)$, with $c=10^{9}$. The norm of the field inside the cylinder is $10^{6}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let us first build that field."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import discretisedfield as df\n",
    "\n",
    "r = 5e-9\n",
    "cell = (0.5e-9, 0.5e-9, 0.5e-9)\n",
    "\n",
    "region = df.Region(p1=(-r, -r, -r), p2=(r, r, r))\n",
    "mesh =  df.Mesh(region=region, cell=cell)\n",
    "\n",
    "def norm_fun(pos):\n",
    "    x, y, z = pos\n",
    "    if x**2 + y**2 + z**2 <= r**2:\n",
    "        return 1e6\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        return 0\n",
    "    \n",
    "def value_fun(pos):\n",
    "    x, y, z = pos\n",
    "    c = 1e9\n",
    "    return (-c*y, c*x, c*z)\n",
    "\n",
    "field = df.Field(mesh, dim=3, value=value_fun, norm=norm_fun)\n",
    "\n",
    "field.plane('z').mpl()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Writing files\n",
    "\n",
    "The main method used for saving field in different files is `discretisedfield.Field.write()`. It takes `filename` as an argument, which is a string with one of the following extensions:\n",
    "- `'.vtk'` for saving in the VTK format\n",
    "- `'.ovf'`, `'.omf'`, `'.ohf'` for saving in the OVF format\n",
    "- `.h5` or `.hdf5` for saving an HDF5 file\n",
    "\n",
    "Let us firstly save the field in the VTK file."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "vtkfilename = 'my_vtk_file.vtk'\n",
    "field.write(vtkfilename)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next, we can save the field in the OVF format and check whether it was created in the current directory."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "ovffilename = 'my_omf_file.omf'\n",
    "field.write(ovffilename)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There are three different possible representations of an OVF file: one ASCII (`txt`) and two binary (`bin4` or `bin8`). ASCII `txt` representation is a default representation when `discretisedfield.Field.write()` is called. If any different representation is required, it can be passed via `representation` argument. For example, if we want to save a binary-8 file:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "field.write(ovffilename, representation='bin8')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In the same way, we can save the HDF5 file:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "hdf5filename = 'my_omf_file.hdf5'\n",
    "field.write(hdf5filename)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Reading files\n",
    "\n",
    "The method for reading field files is a class method `discretisedfield.Field.fromfile()`. By passing a `filename` argument, it reads the file and creates a `discretisedfield.Field` object. It is not required to pass the representation of the OVF file to the `discretisedfield.Field.fromfile()` method, because it can retrieve it from the content of the file.\n",
    "\n",
    "VTK file:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "field_read = df.Field.fromfile(vtkfilename)\n",
    "field_read.plane('z').mpl()  # to compare with the field we wrote into the file"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "OVF file:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "field_read = df.Field.fromfile(ovffilename)\n",
    "field_read.plane('z').mpl()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "HDF5 file:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "field_read = df.Field.fromfile(hdf5filename)\n",
    "field_read.plane('z').mpl()"
   ]
  }
